      <div xml:id="NA167-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">1. itu tōḻi pāṇaṟku vāyiṉ maṟuttatu.
            2. tūtoṭu vanta pāṇaṟkuc colliyatūumām.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. This is how the confidante refused the door to the bard. 2. It is also what [she?] said to the bard how had come with a message.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA167">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            karuṅkōṭṭup puṉṉaik kuṭakkuvāṅku peruñciṉai</l>
<l>            viruntiṉ veṇkuru kārppi ṉāay</l>
<l>            vaṇmakiḻ nāḷavaip paricil peṟṟa</l>
<l>            paṇṇamai neṭuntērp pāṇiyi ṉolikkun</l>
<l>            taṇṇan tuṟaivaṉ ṟūtoṭum vanta </l>
<l>            payaṉṟeri paṉuvaṟ paitīr pāṇa</l>
<l>            niṉvāyp paṇimoḻi kaḷaiyā paṉmāṇ</l>
<l>            putuvī ñāḻaloṭu puṉṉai tāa</l>
<l>            maṇaṅkamaḻ kāṉaṉ māṇala miḻanta</l>
<l>            viṟaiyē relvaḷaik kuṟumakaḷ </l>
<l>            piṟaiyēr tirunutal pāaya pacappē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>O bard, who ends suffering by [so] many words that understand</l>
<l rend="indent4">[just your] profit,</l>
<l>who came with a message from the man of the cool ghat,</l>
<l rend="indent2">where the [well-]prepared long chariot, that has been obtained</l>
<l rend="indent2">as a gift in the assembly on a day of great joy from Āy<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">āay</term> can either be read as the name of that generous chieftain or as absolutive of <term xml:lang="ta">ā</term>: "being/having become like ...".</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent2">sounds rhythmically like the din of the white herons feasting</l>
<l rend="indent3">on the big branches bend to the west of the dark-trunked Puṉṉai tree,</l>
<l>– the humble words from your mouth won't remove</l>
<l rend="indent">the pallor that spread on the brilliant forehead like the crescent moon</l>
<l rend="indent2">of the small woman with bright bangles rising on [her] forearms</l>
<l rend="indent2">who lost her glorious<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">paṉmāṇ</term>: T.V.G. explains this formulaic phrase here as "many times", which seems unavoidable in several contexts (cf. NA 12.5, 71.3), but here it does not seem to make much sense.</note> innocence in the seashore-grove giving fragrance,</l>
<l rend="indent3">where the most glorious new blossoms of the Puṉṉai tree</l>
<l rend="indent4">together with the Ñāḻal are spreading.</l>
        </lg>
